Anyway, thanks for the interesting problem! Here's my solution (in Rust) to the general problem which I believe is easier to prove why it works. (`usize` is an unsigned integer, `&[usize]` is a slice/array view of some unsigned integers, `|params| { expression… }` is a lambda.)

fn num_ways(n: usize, step_sizes: &[usize]) -> usize {
    step_sizes.iter().map(|&step_size| {
        if step_size == n {
            1
        } else if step_size > n {
            0
        } else {
            num_ways(n - step_size, step_sizes)
        }
    })
    .sum()
}

The reason why this works is:
1. the first base case: if the stair is as high (n) as the possible number of steps (step_size), there is exactly one way to reach its top: a leap of exactly n (or step_size) steps.
2. the second base case: if the possible step size exceeds the height of the stair, then it's not possible to get to its top, so that's 0 possible ways.
3. Otherwise, the recursive case: if the step size is strictly smaller than the number of steps in the stair, then one can make a jump of size `step_size`, then count the possible ways of reaching the top from the point one ended up at after the jump.
4. Finally, by trying out every possible step size after every jump (hence, .map), one can figure out the number of possible ways for each step, and the total # of ways is the sum of those partial results, since they are independent of each other.

